The mage floated carefully down the main path, searching for any sign of them.\par
Blinding shafts of sun pierced into the empty space through the outer wall openings.\par
A darkened parking floor, cut up with white triangles into black squares filled with fuzzy grey in between. \par
Yet, in light or in shade, the mage's white cape shined without fail, like clouds hiding the sun. And her orange sigils, dotted all over her button-up and trousers, glowed pure - intense. And her helmet cut into a rounded polyhedron, was so glassy, so glossy that it looked hand painted. \par
Suddenly, from behind, feet scuttled, fleeing for the stairs.\par
She turned and shot herself straight at them. \par
Even though they were at the opposite end, her flight speed was way too good. Plus it was no good running whilst carrying the heavy device. \par
Inches away, her hand reached out, ready to snatch them. \par
\par
But, suddenly, something banged into her helm, stopping her motion dead. \par
"Wha--?!"\par
It was a foot, someone's foot had stomped onto her helmet. And before she could react, it instantly pushed her off. She was thrown into a ragged, spinning mess, bouncing off the ground once before forcefully righting herself and facing her foe. \par
Over in the blur of shadows, she caught the target and the device flee down the stairs. \par
And then, landing on bouncy toes, the cause of her annoyance crouched in the way. A black cat mask, large green eyes, and red hair were the first things she noticed. Very quickly though, the fact that it was clearly a kid made itself clear too. \par
The redhead smirked, ready to go, "Seems you're pretty tough! Lemme guess, magic armor?"\par
Pushing all the immediate questions out of her mind, the mage shook her head and yelled, "Out of my way, you little...trick-or-treater! What even are you dressed up as?! Whatever, leave! I don't have time to babysit!"\par
Her foe scoffed, "You're one to talk about costumes! And if you think I'm such an easy target, then go ahead. Beat me, and get past, Domehead!"\par
"You...fool-girl!"\par
\par
One burst forward threw the mage with max momentum to attack, but the girl held her smile.\par
A furious swing: ducked. \par
The follow-up kick: side-stepped.\par
And an elbow strike: backed away from. \par
But the force of that last strike left them off-balance, if there was such a thing whilst levitating, and the cat-masked foe leaned in, grabbing the mage's arm and flipping them over, aimed for the wall. \par
Quick telekinesis helped soften the impact, and prevent a head-first landing on the way down. But it did nothing to stop their opponent from taunting.\par
"Had enough yet? Or are you ready for me to get serious?" The fighter in black tights mocked, not waiting for an answer. \par
She dashed forward, changing the distance into a memory and the mage could only manage a half-gasp before a strong spin-kick gave her flight straight into the pillar by the wall. One furious stomp crumpled her into her newly formed divot, then came the second and third, pushing her deeper. \par
And the girl had plenty to say, letting each word be punctuated with another vicious kick.\par
"By! The! Way! Name's! \b Not\b0 ! 'Fool Girl'! It's! Lu-cky! Girl!!!" \par
This last stomp shattered the pillar in two, and Lucky Girl hopped back out of range. The huge support fell forward and collapsed onto the mage. Or, it would have if the mage hadn't used a spell. A yellow forcefield domed around her with the hunk of concrete floating effortlessly above. She pulled herself up and shuffled aside, leaving the pillar to smash halfway into the floor. \par
The weird feeling, buzzing in her head throughout the fight, finally became recognisable to the young hero, "You! You\b  \b0 have a Charm of Bezel!! Levitation!"\par
The mage paced back and forth, patting dirt off their scuffed outfit, to little noticeable effect. \par
"Of course! You're totally channelling it's power to fly! Plus whatever mega-strong spells you've got on for armor and strength."\par
No answer as her foe pulled her cape around to her front, dusting it off as well with increasingly wide sweeps of the hand. \par
Lucky Girl squared up, "Well I can't let a baddie like you hold onto it. Let's make it easy, give me the charm, and we don't have to see who'd win in a round 2." She concluded, leaning in slightly.\par
With one last exaggerated sweep of her coat, the mage sent her arm straight up at the hero.\par
"Repulsa!"\par
Green eyes shocked wide were sent flying away at speed down the lot.  \par
"Levitas"\par
And her flight backwards curved up, bashing hard into the ceiling. \par
"Comboros!"\par
And finally, she was sent straight into the ground.\par
\par
"Oof!" \par
She landed rearside and immediately jumped up to find...no one.\par
"Ugh, where could they've...?" \par
She stopped herself and pulled her thoughts in a more useful direction, "She was after that person. So, she's wherever they are...but where?"\par
She walked a tiny circle, "Couldn't have gone far. Running outside seems super risky now. Especially with that heavy whatever-it-was that they had. Would be better to just hunker down somewhere and hide. And Domehead's gotta know that too...so--woooah!"\par
The floor, and walls, and pillars and everything else shook violently, and she knew instantly to go to the ground floor, "No! No! No! Please don't cave in the place!"\par
\par
"I KNOW YOU ARE STILL IN HERE!!"\par
The voice boomed almost as loud as the rocking building. Lucky Girl continued sprinting down the stairs.\par
\par
"SHOW YOURSELF WITHIN ONE MINUTE OR I. \b WILL\b0 . COLLAPSE THIS BUILDING!!"\par
Whilst the young hero wasn't sure tearing apart the builiding was in the mage's best interests, at all, the shaking was more than enough to seem convincing.\par
\par
"HURRY UP! YOUR WINDOW FOR ESCAPING IS CLOSING!!"\par
She almost reached the bottom of the stairs as she heard a loud cry.\par
\par
"Please! Please, don't crush me! I give up, I'm here!"\par
The masked girl touched the ground floor and slinked behind a pillar to watch the person, carrying the boxy contraption, walk to the mage, visibly shaken even more than the building.\par
"I have half a mind to tear you in half after all I've been through! But...it's finally over."\par
"Urgh, I need to do something fast. Can't just let 'em just leave," Lucky Girl whispered to herself, "Alright...might as well try..."\par
She lifted a palm and called out the spell, "Gallius interruptus!"\par
A strong wind picked up the mage, twisting and spinning them upwards to smash into the ceiling.\par
The would-be kidnapee was yelled at, "Hey! You! Run!"\par
Immediately, they went for the exit, their path then quickly covered by the super charged kid. \par
After a few seconds, the mage fell down with a thud on her butt but sprang right up and, with a voice even louder than before, screamed, "YOU ARE A PAIN! I. WILL. END YOU!! REVOLTA!!"\par
Her magic push sent Lucky Girl flying back again, this time straight into a fire hydrant across the street, which left her backside and in front of an empty coffeeshop. \par
"LEVITAS!"\par
Struggling to get up, she felt herself lifted quickly and realised what was coming next. \par
Her back banged into an overarching lightpost, "Urgh! Not this time!" \par
She quickly grabbed on the horizontal post, putting all her superhuman strength into pulling herself into a tight swing and flinging herself backwards, out of the spell's range and onto the coffeeshop roof. \par
"YOU DO NOT GET TO RUN!!" \par
The mage leapt up, soaring over the building and scanning for her opponent.\par
Nothing. \par
They spun their head around, looking every way. Suddenly, something called out from behind.\par
"Hey, Fish Bowl! You're not the only one who can fly!" \par
Turning showed Lucky Girl on some sort of fast-moving, giant, flying square. And with a punch primed to hit.\par
*\b BAM\b0 *\par
"Guuuhhh!!" \par
The hit sent the mage over the coffeeshop to smash right into the parking lot of a restaurant behind it, making quite a dent in the concrete and skidding over onto the sidewalk. \par
Lucky Girl landed the hoverboard nearby and ran over to her barely crawling foe. "Woah, still moving, huh? You are super tough. But, you can't move too much. So, lemme just..."\par
Using a chain from the parking lot entranceway, she tied the mage to a nearby light pole, making sure to give one good finger flick on the helmet. \par
"Just rest a while, till the cops come for you! Ha ha! And that's another win for Lucky Girl!"\par
A loud blast took her out of her celebration, reminding her of the dangers outside and so she hurried back onto the hoverboard, "Right, better go see if the Dweeb needs help!" \par

